</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[121,1089,1442,1504]" pageId="16" pageNumber="355">
Named in reference to the narrow body shape, with Latin adjective 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giron &amp; Franz" authorityYear="2010" box="[868,922,1443,1468]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Apodrosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="artus">
<emphasis box="[868,922,1443,1468]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="355">artus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
meaning “narrow” (
<bibRefCitation author="Brown, R. W." bookContentInfo="882 pp." box="[190,338,1477,1504]" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, DC" pageId="16" pageNumber="355" refId="ref39480" refString="Brown, R. W. (1956) Composition of scientific words, revised edition. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, DC, 882 pp." title="Composition of scientific words, revised edition" type="book" year="1956">Brown 1956</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
